            "V. LLM Review (30pts)": {
              "5.1 Algorithm correctness (12)": "6/12 — Implements the core accept/reject test using min(1, p_target/q_draft) and resamples on rejection from relu(p_target - p_draft) with renormalization, which is directionally the right rejection-sampling form. However, it is not lossless/correct as written: (1) it special-cases temperature=0 with a different (non-RS) rule, so the claimed distributional guarantee is not unified; (2) it uses probabilities derived from temperature-scaled softmax, which is fine if both models are compared under the same sampling distribution, but the implementation mixes verification indexing and an extra initial \"next_token\" step that shifts the usual SD loop, making it easy to be off-by-one with which conditional distribution is being compared; (3) acceptance/resampling is hard-coded to batch size 1 via [0, ...] indexing, breaking correctness for B>1; (4) on rejection it does not properly ensure subsequent draft tokens and caches are discarded/realigned in a mathematically clean way (it breaks but leaves KV state management inconsistent).",
              "5.2 Engineering quality (10)": "5/10 — Target verification is done in a single forward pass over (1 + gamma) tokens, satisfying parallel verification. KV rollback uses tensor slicing (zero-copy views) for keep_len>0, which is good. However, the engine repeatedly uses torch.cat to grow sequences and to build draft token tensors (costly reallocations), and KV handling is inconsistent: rollback uses keep_len derived from idx length rather than explicit cached lengths, and the comment indicates uncertainty. Draft KV is also advanced token-by-token and then conditionally advanced again, making state fragile. Overall efficiency and cache correctness are not robust.",
              "5.3 Completeness and robustness (8)": "6/8 — Includes both baseline autoregressive sampling and speculative decoding, supports gamma, and has temperature>0 stochastic sampling plus a temperature=0 greedy path. But robustness is limited: batch size >1 is not supported (hard-coded indexing), end-of-sequence/stop-token handling is absent, probability computation for temperature=0 is a one-hot hack rather than a principled degeneration of the RS path, and KV/cache length bookkeeping is not clearly correct in all branches.",
              "Overall comment": "Core speculative decoding structure is present (draft propose, target verify in parallel, accept/reject with residual resampling, KV slicing rollback), but the implementation is not reliably lossless due to batch-1 assumptions, off-by-one/state-flow fragility around the extra initial token step, and shaky KV alignment on rejection. Engineering is functional but not optimized because of repeated torch.cat reallocations and unclear cache-length management.",
              "Evaluation model": "openai/gpt-5.2"
            }
          }
